node.title: 'Much more important than Omicron right now': US experts issue a COVID warning
node.description: While the world waits anxiously for information about Omicron, experts warn that Delta is still the dominant variant across the globe. An outbreak at an American high school reunion shows the power of the virus — and the potency of vaccines.

node.title: Search first believed family missing for 17 days likely swept into sea
node.description: The team searching for a man and his three children in a remote part of King Country in September initially thought the family were most likely taken by the ocean.

node.title: Chanel, TikTok and the Beauty Advent Calendar Controversy
node.description: Some social media users are not feeling the Christmas spirit — or this box of mini lipsticks and branded stickers.

node.title: Dictionary.com's Word of the Year Might Be a Surprising Choice for Some, Site Says
node.description: "In the past few decades, the term has evolved to take on a more nuanced and specific meaning," the website's John Kelly said about the word "allyship."

node.title: Justin Bieber Performs to Packed Crowd in Saudi Arabia Despite Activists' Calls to Cancel
node.description: Justin Bieber closed the Saudi Arabian Grand Prix with a concert despite calls from activists to boycott the country for their human rights violations.

node.title: Norwegian Cruise Line Ship That Reported COVID Cases Made Stops in 3 Countries
node.description: The cruise ship stopped in Honduras, Mexico and Belize with the 10 infected passengers.

node.title: U.S. to Diplomatically Boycott Beijing Olympics, China Promises 'Resolute Countermeasures'
node.description: The boycott does not extend to athletes, and White House press secretary Jen Psaki said competitors will have the country's "full support."

node.title: US confirms diplomatic boycott of Beijing Winter Olympics over 'ongoing genocide' in Xinjiang
node.description: White House spokeswoman Jen Psaki says the US will not contribute to the fanfare of the Beijing Winter Olympics in light of China's "egregious" human rights abuses.

node.title: Carrie Mae Weems Sets the Stage and Urges Action
node.description: In “The Shape of Things” at the Park Avenue Armory, the artist tells us how we got to this political moment, and asks us to decide what comes next.

node.title: Dancing Grannies Make First Return After Losing 4 Members in Waukesha Parade Crash
node.description: The Dancing Grannies marched arm-in-arm at the Franklin Christmas parade on Saturday to honor those who passed.

node.title: Treasury Wants to Regulate All-Cash Real Estate Deals to Crack Down on Money Laundering
node.description: Only 12 U.S. cities required title insurance companies to disclose peoples' identities making all-cash purchases of $300,000 homes through shell companies.

node.title: Tennis bodies at odds over Peng Shuai
node.description: The governing body of tennis says it won't be following the Women's Tennis Association in suspending tournaments in China because it "does not want to punish a billion people".

node.title: Australian PM behind in polls and beset by division, faces tough road to re-election
node.description: Analysis - A chaotic parliament session has left Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison seeking a reset as his conservative coalition trails in opinion polls and infighting derails his legislative…

node.title: Covid-19: Tauranga police station high-risk spot, pupil tests positive
node.description: Tauranga police station has been listed this evening as a high risk location of interest for Covid-19, and a primary school pupil in the region has also tested positive.

node.title: In ‘Landscapers,’ True Crime Meets Hollywood Fantasy
node.description: The HBO mini-series stars Olivia Colman and David Thewlis as a British couple convicted of killing the wife’s parents and burying them in the backyard.

node.title: After 8 Wolves Are Poisoned, Oregon Police Ask for Help
node.description: From February to July, an entire pack and three other wolves were found dead from poisoning, according to the authorities.

node.title: Stricter coronavirus testing rules take effect for travelers flying to the U.S.
node.description: Inbound travelers must now show a negative result from a test taken no more than a day before departure, a requirement some say may be hard to satisfy.

node.title: Pope Francis Accepts Archbishop's Resignation Due to 'Gossip' About Relationship With Woman
node.description: Archbishop Michel Aupetit allegedly had an "ambiguous" relationship with a woman in 2012.

node.title: Minneapolis' First Black Police Chief Who Led Department During Floyd Death to Retire
node.description: Medaria Arradondo said that "the impacts of Floyd's killing will stay with me forever," but they did not factor into his decision to retire next month.

node.title: David Perdue Running for Georgia Governor to Make Sure Stacey Abrams 'Never' Holds Office
node.description: Perdue's entry into the race intensifies the Republican primary in a state that flipped blue in last year's elections.

node.title: Concerning levels of heavy metals found in Indigenous people living beside world's biggest manganese-producing mine
node.description: Tests on the hair and nails of children and adults living in Angurugu, on Groote Eylandt, have shown "concerning" levels of manganese, according to the local lands council.

node.title: 'We had them cold': Inside the day Australia lost the unlosable Ashes Test
node.description: With the home side facing odds of 500-1 to win at Headingley in 1981, two stoic Englishmen stood in the way of Kim Hughes leading his Australians to a famous victory — and it's a string of events the former captain has been trying to forget since.

node.title: Why everyone with a mortgage should be watching the Australian dollar
node.description: When the Aussie dollar shows signs of moving significantly one way or the other economists take notice. And it's starting to fall, writes David Taylor.

node.title: Omicron outbreak in South Korea throws President's planned Australia trip into disarray
node.description: Plans for the South Korean President to visit Australia for strategic and economic talks are up in the air, with his nation battling an outbreak of the COVID-19 Omicron variant.

node.title: Up to 900 bison at Yellowstone to be killed or relocated this winter
node.description: Bison routinely leave Yellowstone and head north into Montana each winter, raising concerns that the animals could spread brucellosis to cattle.

node.title: Kentucky Derby winner Medina Spirit dies following workout

node.title: In the Mountain West, the ‘Dirty’ Soda Rush Is On

node.title: Grammys Remove Taylor Swift and Others From Olivia Rodrigo Nomination

node.title: Heeding Warning Signs Before School Shootings

node.title: A Kennedy Center Honors With the Presidential Box Used as Intended
node.description: Former President Donald J. Trump did not attend the tribute, but President Biden was on hand as Bette Midler, Joni Mitchell, Berry Gordy, Justino Díaz and Lorne Michaels were honored.
